&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 54.2pt;&quot;&gt;Newton also took a deep interest in Alchemy. Although most of the Alchemical papers are in Cambridge, the NLI possesses one unique page. It is a part of Newton&apos;s copy of an English translation made in 1624 of &lt;i&gt;the Exposition of the Hieroglyphical figures&lt;/i&gt; written by the famous French Alchemist Nicholas Flamel. Newton sketched Flamel&apos;s symbolic figures, and described in the text above&amp;#160; their Alchemical role.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 54.2pt;&quot;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

