&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Elimelech Basch&apos;s eldest daughter, Bluma (Perhiya), was the only one of the Basch family who survived. &amp;#160;Bluma emigrated to Israel, changed her name to Perhiya and built a new family. &amp;#160;Perhiya has three children, many grandchildren and a newborn great granddaughter. &amp;#160;She is now 87 years old. She is still an active volounteer in her hometown Lydda (Lod). &amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Photo&lt;/b&gt;: &amp;#160;In the center Perhiya receiving a token of gratitude from the city of Lydda for her long years as a volunteer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Photo&lt;/b&gt;: Perhiya&apos;s testimony, given in January 1956, regarding the murder of her family. &amp;#160;The testimony was given to the Yad Vashem museum for the memory of the Holocaust in Jerusalem, Israel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
