&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst&quot; style=&quot; margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 25.45pt; margin-bottom: .0001pt; margin-left: 36.0pt; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Jean Fran&lt;span style=&quot; font-family: &apos;Calibri Light&apos;, sans-serif;&quot;&gt;&#231;&lt;/span&gt;ois Daumont made this beautiful map of Jerusalem in 1780, yet it was made after a map originally drawn almost 300 years beforehand,&amp;#160; in 1486, following the pilgrimage of Bernhard of Breydenbach to Jerusalem in 1483.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoListParagraphCxSpLast&quot; style=&quot; margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 25.45pt; margin-bottom: .0001pt; margin-left: 36.0pt; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Daumont chooses to identify Christian and Muslim monuments by a Cross or Crescent, but does not name the Muslim monuments. Daumont chooses to call the mosques on the Temple Mount in fact by their Crusader name: &quot;Templum Salomonis&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
