&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Dapper (1635-1689), who never travelled outside Holland, collected much information about the Holy Land and many other countries. His realistic map (1677) relied on a Bernardino Amico&apos;s map who was a Franciscan monk in Jerusalem between 1593-1597. Amico, in his turn, copied a map made by the Franciscan monk Antonio d&apos;Angelis who had served in Jerusalem a few years before; his map continued to be copied by generations of Christian map-makers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoListParagraphCxSpLast&quot; style=&quot; margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 25.45pt; margin-bottom: .0001pt; margin-left: 36.0pt; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;The map does not identify the religious affiliation of the monuments by a Cross or Crescent, and calls the Mosques on the Temple Mount &#8211; &quot;The Pagan Church&quot;.&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
