&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; align=&quot;left&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 35.45pt; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;Alongside the Torah (the Pentateuch), which is the written&amp;#160; law of the Jews,&amp;#160; there developed an oral tradition of interpretation. This tradition was put down in writing and sealed in the beginning of the third century CE by Rabbi Yehudah Ha-Nassi , the head of the Jewish&amp;#160; Assembly, since it was feared at that time that the tradition would be lost. The &lt;i&gt;Mishnah&lt;/i&gt; is considered to be a source of religious legal authority second only to the written Torah.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; align=&quot;left&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 35.45pt; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; align=&quot;left&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 35.45pt; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;photo: A paragraph from the Mishnah, preserved in the Cairo Genizah: &quot;Rabbi Yohanan said: Whoever fulfills the Torah despite poverty, will ultimately fulfill it in wealth; but whoever neglects the Torah because of wealth, will ultimately neglect it in poverty.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
