}
--&gt;
&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot; style=&quot; text-align: left; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;Although from a Jewish family, Kafka&apos;s Jewish education was minimal and amounted to a few visits a year at the Synagogue. Yet, in 1911, having been enchanted by a Yiddish theatre performance, he took up the study of Yiddish language and literature; as a consequence of this his interest in Judaism was aroused. During the early 1920&apos;s in Prague Kafka started studying modern &lt;span style=&quot; color: red;&quot;&gt;Hebrew&lt;/span&gt;. Under the influence of his last lover, Dora Diamant, who came from an Orthodox Jewish family, Kafka even showed interest in the &lt;span style=&quot; color: red;&quot;&gt;Talmud&lt;/span&gt;! It was during that time, when they were living in Berlin, that Kafka took classes in Judaism.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
