&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;DefaultStyle&quot; style=&quot; margin-left: 36.0pt; text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;Upon Newton&apos;s death in Cambridge in 1727, his relatives, the Conduitts, claimed his papers. Newton&apos;s papers reflected an array of various interests and occupations: papers in Mathematics and Physics, &amp;#160;documents written as part of his function as head of the Royal Mint and President of the Royal Society, and&amp;#160; the less known and more intriguing papers on Theology ,History and Alchemy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;EditLive! 7.6.2.10&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;TheBrain 7.0.4.5&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;
&lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;
&lt;!--
body {
font-family: Arial;  font-size: small;  background: #ffffff;  color: #000000;
}
p {
margin-top: 0pt;  margin-bottom: 0pt;
}
--&gt;
&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Being integrated into German-speaking society, Jews such as Zweig and Benjamin saw themselves as part of European society, and conceived Jewish identity as a universal phenomenon which lived in harmony with their Europeanism. With the rise of the Nazis to power their world fell apart. Many such Jewish intellectuals including Zweig, Benjamin, the famous poet Elsa Lasker-&lt;span style=&quot; font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 115%; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: black; background: white;&quot;&gt;Sch&#252;ler&amp;#160;&lt;/span&gt;, the poet and writer Albert Ehrenstein, and many more, sent their archives to the National Library in Palestine in order to save what they could of their life&apos;s achievements and records.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt; 
&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;EditLive! 7.6.2.10&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta name=&quot;generator&quot; content=&quot;TheBrain 7.0.4.5&quot; /&gt;
&lt;meta http-equiv=&quot;Content-Type&quot; content=&quot;text/html; charset=UTF-8&quot; /&gt;
&lt;style type=&quot;text/css&quot;&gt;
&lt;!--
body {
font-family: Arial;  font-size: small;  background: #ffffff;  color: #000000;
}
p {
margin-top: 0pt;  margin-bottom: 0pt;
}
--&gt;
&lt;/style&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Scroll seen here was donated to the NLI by the Adini-Edel family.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Unlike the Torah scrolls usually used in Synagogues, this is a miniature scroll,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;written in micrographic script.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It was either written or owned by a well-known Jewish scholar from eastern&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Europe by the name of Rabbai Judah Edel (1757 &#8211; 1828), who in his capacity as a&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;preacher travelled much and needed a compact version of the Torah to take with&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;him. After it was donated to the library it turned out that one of the library&apos;s most&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;experienced manuscript experts was a descendent of Rabbai Edel.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;

&lt;!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC &quot;-//W3C//DTD XHTML 1.0 Transitional//EN&quot; &quot;http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml1/DTD/xhtml1-transitional.dtd&quot;&gt;&lt;html xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml&quot;&gt;
